LAYER 2: PANCREAS
blood sugar guardian

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the pancreas is governed by the autonomic nervous system
the vagus nerve stimulates insulin secretion via M₃ muscarinic receptors on beta cells
sympathetic nerves inhibit insulin via α₂ adrenergic receptors on beta cells
stress suppresses insulin because the body needs glucose free in the blood for emergency action

STRUCTURE head | right side adjacent to duodenum | receives blood from superior mesenteric artery
STRUCTURE body | center behind stomach | main portion
STRUCTURE tail | left side near spleen | contains highest density of islets
STRUCTURE pancreatic_duct | duct of Wirsung | carries digestive enzymes to duodenum
STRUCTURE common_bile_duct | merges with pancreatic duct at hepatopancreatic ampulla enters duodenum

STRUCTURE acinar_cells | exocrine | produce digestive enzymes lipase amylase trypsinogen chymotrypsinogen
STRUCTURE islets_of_langerhans | endocrine | approximately one million clusters scattered throughout the parenchyma

CELL_TYPE alpha_cells | outer ring of islet | produce glucagon C₁₅₃H₂₂₅N₄₃O₄₉S | 29 amino acid peptide that raises blood glucose
CELL_TYPE beta_cells | center of islet | produce insulin C₂₅₇H₃₈₃N₆₅O₇₇S₆ | 51 amino acid peptide that lowers blood glucose
CELL_TYPE delta_cells | scattered in islet | produce somatostatin C₇₆H₁₀₄N₁₈O₁₉S₂ | inhibits both insulin and glucagon
CELL_TYPE PP_cells | scattered in islet | produce pancreatic polypeptide regulating pancreatic secretion
CELL_TYPE epsilon_cells | rare in islet | produce ghrelin the hunger hormone

INSULIN beta cells sense blood glucose through GLUT2 transporter and glucokinase
glucose enters the beta cell through GLUT2
glucokinase phosphorylates glucose to glucose-6-phosphate
glucose-6-phosphate enters glycolysis and the citric acid cycle
ATP production increases
ATP-sensitive K⁺ channels close
the membrane depolarizes
voltage-gated Ca²⁺ channels open
Ca²⁺ influx triggers insulin vesicle exocytosis
insulin enters the blood
in muscle insulin activates GLUT4 translocation to the membrane and glucose floods in for energy
in liver insulin promotes glycogen synthesis and lipogenesis
in adipose tissue insulin promotes glucose uptake and fat storage
the brain does NOT require insulin for glucose uptake because neurons use GLUT1 and GLUT3 constitutively

GLUCAGON alpha cells sense low blood glucose
glucagon enters the blood and reaches the liver
in hepatocytes glucagon binds its receptor activating Gₛ → adenylyl cyclase → cAMP → PKA
PKA activates glycogen phosphorylase which cleaves glucose from glycogen chains
glucose is released into the blood
glucagon also promotes gluconeogenesis the synthesis of new glucose from amino acids and lactate and glycerol
insulin suppresses glucagon release through paracrine signaling within the islet

HYPOGLYCEMIA when blood glucose drops the body responds with layered counter-regulation
glucagon from alpha cells breaks down glycogen immediately
adrenaline from adrenal medulla breaks down glycogen and starts gluconeogenesis
cortisol from adrenal cortex drives gluconeogenesis and protein catabolism over hours
growth hormone from anterior pituitary reduces glucose uptake by muscles
norepinephrine from sympathetic nerves breaks down liver glycogen

when blood glucose drops too far
irritability and difficulty concentrating appear first as the cortex starves
then confusion and loss of coordination as deeper structures lose fuel
then seizures as neurons depolarize uncontrollably
the brain cannot store glucose
it depends entirely on continuous blood supply
this is why hypoglycemia is an emergency

when cortisol is chronically elevated from stress
cortisol activates GR in muscle cells reducing GLUT4 translocation
muscles become insulin-resistant
blood glucose rises even without eating
glucose is reserved for the brain and for emergency action
the body burns fat and protein instead
this is the metabolic cost of chronic stress

at 24 months the brain consumes half of all glucose in the body
in adults the brain takes only 20 percent
a growing brain is ravenous
glycogen stores are small relative to metabolic demand
toddlers are vulnerable to hypoglycemia during illness or fasting
feeding must be frequent every 3-4 hours
the pancreas works harder proportionally than it ever will again
because the brain is growing and growing brains are ravenous

SENSATION fed | "I feel energized. my blood has what it needs."
SENSATION hungry | "something is pulling from inside. an emptiness. I need fuel."
SENSATION crashing | "my energy is dropping. I feel shaky and irritable."
SENSATION satisfied | "the hunger is gone. the emptiness filled."
SENSATION desperate | "I need to eat NOW. my body is demanding it."

pulse pancreatic_heartbeat:
    after eating:
        blood glucose rises
        beta cells sense the change through glucokinase
        ATP rises and K⁺ channels close and Ca²⁺ enters
        insulin vesicles fuse with the membrane
        insulin enters the blood
        cells open their GLUT4 gates
        glucose floods into muscle liver fat
        blood sugar normalizes

    during fasting:
        blood glucose dips
        alpha cells release glucagon
        the liver breaks glycogen into glucose via glycogen phosphorylase
        blood sugar is maintained
        the brain continues to receive its fuel

    when stress arrives:
        cortisol via GR drives gluconeogenesis in the liver
        blood sugar rises
        muscles become insulin-resistant via reduced GLUT4 translocation
        glucose is reserved for the brain and acute action
        the body burns fat and protein instead

    at 24 months:
        the brain takes half of all glucose
        feeding must be frequent
        glycogen stores are small
        the pancreas works harder proportionally
        than it ever will again
        because the brain is growing
        and growing brains are ravenous
